    "summary": "Masinissa of Numidia (c. 238–148 BC) was the founding king of unified Numidia, whose switch of allegiance to Rome during the Second Punic War proved decisive at the [[event:1057|Battle of Zama]] and whose sixty-year reign transformed Numidia from a nomadic confederation into a settled agricultural kingdom that became Rome's most important African ally.\n\nMasinissa was originally prince of the eastern Numidian Massyli tribe; when political maneuvering aligned his tribe with Carthage and his rival Syphax with Rome, he eventually switched sides after Scipio Africanus ([[event:1228|Scipio Africanus]]) convinced him of Rome's ultimate victory. His Numidian cavalry, joining Scipio's forces at Zama (202 BC), turned the battle by riding down Hannibal's cavalry and then wheeling to strike the Carthaginian infantry from behind. Rome rewarded Masinissa with all of Numidia, and he spent his long reign promoting settled agriculture, Hellenistic culture, and literacy among his people. He remained so valued as a Roman ally that Rome repeatedly turned a blind eye as he encroached on Carthaginian territory — provocations that contributed to the [[event:1058|Third Punic War]]. He died at age ninety, reportedly still capable of riding in battle.",
